Five Critical Questions You Must Ask (and Their Answers)

1. How will Arvdoul handle the hybrid friend/follower model seamlessly, and how does the backend differentiate between personal connections and public creator audiences?

Arvdoul must support both symmetric friendships (mutual follow) and asymmetric follower/creator relationships. The social graph must be stored in a single follows collection but with a relationshipType field (friend, follow, blocked). The UI for profiles will show different stats: for a user’s profile, display “Friends” (mutual) and “Followers” (total). When a user follows another, if the other follows back, both records are upgraded to relationshipType: 'friend' atomically. This enables dual behavior: a friend’s feed shows in the “Friends” tab (a curated, chronological feed), while a creator’s public posts appear in the “For You” feed based on algorithmic ranking. Notifications are also contextual: a friend’s action can show more detail (e.g., “Your friend John liked your photo”), while a follower’s action is generic (“Someone liked your post”). The backend enforces this by checking the relationship type when generating notifications.

---

2. What is the exact monetization loop that ensures Arvdoul generates massive revenue while keeping users engaged and never feeling exploited?

The loop hinges on a dual‑currency system: Arvdoul Coins (purchased with real money, used for gifts, boosts, stickers) and Creator Credits (earned only from paid interactions, convertible to cash at Level 20). Users earn XP for all positive actions (posting, engaging, spending coins). XP drives a 20‑level ladder. Reaching Level 10 allows earning Creator Credits, but withdrawal is locked until Level 20. This means the vast majority of users are paying or watching ads while they climb the ladder, generating revenue. The platform takes a cut of all coin purchases and a transaction fee on creator cash‑outs. Ads are contextual, non‑tracking, and premium users see none. This aligns incentives: users are motivated to create and engage to level up, spending coins to boost their posts (which gives them more XP), all while Arvdoul profits.

---

3. Without external investment, what is the most cost‑effective yet scalable architecture for a React Native app that can compete with native apps?

Use React Native with Expo for the core UI, but leverage native modules for performance‑critical features (camera, video player, WebRTC). For the backend, Firebase serves as the primary database, but we offload expensive operations: Mux for video transcoding and streaming (priced per minute, far cheaper than building your own), Algolia for search, and Cloud Run for machine learning inference. To keep costs low, we aggressively cache with Redis and use Firestore TTLs and scheduled functions to delete ephemeral data. The app will be under 150MB by using code splitting, Hermes engine, and optimized assets. This stack can support millions of users before requiring a move to a fully custom backend.

---

4. How will Arvdoul’s algorithm be transparent and controllable yet still incredibly effective?

Arvdoul will publish the source code of its feed ranking model. Inside the app, a “Why this post?” button reveals the score breakdown (e.g., “30% from friends, 20% because you liked similar content, 10% recency”). Users can adjust the weights directly in their settings (stored in user_feed_preferences). The algorithm itself uses a two‑tower neural network trained on user interaction signals, but the input features and weight multipliers are exposed. This is technically impossible for TikTok because their algorithm is a proprietary black box. Arvdoul’s openness becomes its moat.

---

5. What is the strategy to make Arvdoul’s UI/UX so beautiful and addictive that users never want to leave, while remaining light and fast?

The design follows three principles: fluid motion, depth, and personalization. Every transition uses spring animations with a shared physics model. The interface adapts to the user’s behavior: frequently used buttons grow larger, color accents shift based on the time of day, and the feed background subtly reflects the dominant color of the current post. All lists use FlashList with pre‑computed layouts to guarantee 60 FPS on mid‑range devices. The result is an app that feels alive, responsive, and uniquely tailored to each person.

